{"type":"message","id":"956db0ee","parentId":"637d932e","timestamp":"2026-05-29T09:09:53.533Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"curl seems to hang. Git operations are timing out. There's clearly a network issue reaching GitHub. Let me kill the background processes and diagnose.\n\nActually wait, curl is hanging too, which means the network itself to github is having issues. But earlier the backup log shows it successfully pushed on May 29 at 03:05. So something might have changed since then.\n\nLet me think about what happened:\n1. The backup ran at 03:05 on May 29, did the git push, and the local repo has commit `03ded9a` from May 29\n2. But when I do `git fetch origin main`, the remote shows the latest as `1046fe7` (May 28), not May 29\n\n\n3. This means that push from 03:05 either didn't actually reach the remote, or the push appeared to succeed but actually failed silently — the \"fatal: HTTP/2 stream 1 was not closed cleanly\" error followed by \"Backup pushed to GitHub\" suggests the error occurred but then something made it seem like the push succeeded when it didn't\n\nThe \"Message sent: om_x100b6ebd50409ca0c3d5cdf28749e83\" could mean it sent a Feishu notification claiming success, but the actual git push never completed. So locally the repo thinks it has May 29 committed and pushed, but the remote doesn't have it.\n\nNow I'm realizing the push itself was blocked due to that HTTP/2 error, yet somehow the script's logic interpreted this as a successful push anyway. The local backup exists in `/tmp/openclaw-backup-clone`, but I can't push it to GitHub right now because the connection is timing out and commands are hanging. I need to kill those hanging processes and give the user a status update.\n","thinkingSignature":"743b6511e2d7d719ecdc8eb8e18328105a225be268cc7e3020de56f1b18c5c9a"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_d6cw9co6we4e_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"kill $(jobs -p) 2>/dev/null; pkill -f \"git.